Mpumalanga police have launched a manhunt for six suspects after they bombed a drop safe at Viva filling station on Thursday. It is reported the crime happened in the early hours of the morning when a group of unknown men entered the garage at Belfast village, near Mkhuhlu. One of the residents who lives close to the garage Mandla Mkhatshwa (34) told Daily Sun that he was woken up by a huge sound but didn’t know where it was coming from. “I went out of my room to investigate and several minutes later, I saw a group of men coming out of the filling station running,” he said. Mpumalanga police spokesman Brigadier Leonard Hlathi confirmed a drop safe was bombed at the mentioned petrol station. He said the police received information that six unknown male suspects were seen walking around the business premises and later a sound of the bombing was heard at the garage. “At the scene, they found that the front door office and drop safe inside has been bombed, and an undisclosed amount of money was taken,” he said. “No one was injured during the bombing and police are investigating a case of business robbery. We request anyone with information to assist the police as soon as possible so that the suspects can be arrested,” Hlathi said. He urged the public to contact Lieutenant-Colonel Dudu Shabangu on 082 469 2569 or Crime Stop on 08600 10111.